<div id="review_253369426" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/253369426" />
    <a title="Manray9" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7288965-manray9"><img alt="Manray9" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518315005p2/7288965.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/253369426?book_show_action=true">Dec 30, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manray9" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manray9" href="/user/show/7288965-manray9">Manray9</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140186031" href="/book/show/2634481-and-quiet-flows-the-don">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7288965-manray9?shelf=russian-lit">russian-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer253369426" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12354731004786479780">I am glad to see <i>Quiet Flows the Don</i> is back in print in English. Sholokhov won the Nobel Prize for this novel of war and revolution among the Don Cossack host. Although painted across a backdrop of history, it is primarily the love story of Gregor and Aksinya. As much of great 20th century Russian literature, the style harks back to Tolstoy, but the subject matter is undeniably Soviet. Published in 1929, <i>Quiet Flows the Don</i> was the pinnacle of Sholokhov&apos;s career. He never again produced a work </span>
  <span id="freeText12354731004786479780" style="display:none">I am glad to see <i>Quiet Flows the Don</i> is back in print in English. Sholokhov won the Nobel Prize for this novel of war and revolution among the Don Cossack host. Although painted across a backdrop of history, it is primarily the love story of Gregor and Aksinya. As much of great 20th century Russian literature, the style harks back to Tolstoy, but the subject matter is undeniably Soviet. Published in 1929, <i>Quiet Flows the Don</i> was the pinnacle of Sholokhov's career. He never again produced a work to compare, although to be fair to him, his career coincided with the height of Stalinist conformity in the arts. This was an era when simply being a famous writer was dangerous - think of the careers of Pasternak, Babel, and Pilnyak. If Sholokhov descended into the role of a party hack churning out the obligatory Socialist Realist pap, at least he lived to a ripe old age.<br /><br />I have never understood the conventional English translation of the book's title as <i>Quiet Flows the Don</i>. In Russian it is <i>Тихий Дон</i>, literally <i>The Quiet Don</i>. Did the original translator, Stephen Garry, believe it would be confused with a story of a taciturn British academic? </span>
  <a data-text-id="12354731004786479780" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


