<div id="review_2752366617" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2752366617" />
    <a title="Aravind Pradhyumnan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67054296-aravind-pradhyumnan"><img alt="Aravind Pradhyumnan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492629550p2/67054296.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2752366617?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aravind Pradhyumnan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aravind Pradhyumnan" href="/user/show/67054296-aravind-pradhyumnan">Aravind Pradhyumnan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/67054296-aravind-pradhyumnan?shelf=hi-fi-and-classics">hi-fi-and-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2752366617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9856108981114160112">June 4th 2019 - June 4th 2021. Two years. Four books. Ten years of Grigory&apos;s life. The Melekhovs. The cossacks. War. Revolution. And Aksinya. <i>And Quite Flows The Don</i> is indeed about these things, but if anyone asked me what it is about, I&apos;d have to mention two points. <br/><br/>One: the bitterness and terrible sorrows of life. Imagine how bleak &quot;Russian war fiction&quot; sounds. This story is ten times bleaker than that. And yes, while some pages have made me feel unmatched existential anguish, some have given</span>
  <span id="freeText9856108981114160112" style="display:none">June 4th 2019 - June 4th 2021. Two years. Four books. Ten years of Grigory's life. The Melekhovs. The cossacks. War. Revolution. And Aksinya. <i>And Quite Flows The Don</i> is indeed about these things, but if anyone asked me what it is about, I'd have to mention two points. <br /><br />One: the bitterness and terrible sorrows of life. Imagine how bleak "Russian war fiction" sounds. This story is ten times bleaker than that. And yes, while some pages have made me feel unmatched existential anguish, some have given me joy and laughter. There are a variety of both vile and lovely characters in these books but even Darya, the most hopeful and optimistic of the lot, isn't without her own bitterness and sorrows in life. <br /><br />Two: the wild independence of Grigory. In his youth, this manifested as a callous selfishness, and in his old age, as political neutrality in wars he lacked conviction for the sides he fought on. Grigory had done many hateful things in his life, but he was always growing and maturing into someone better. Ultimately, war and his desire for freedom would strip him of everything dear to him. <br /><br />This is a sad story, but it makes me grateful to live in a time where peace is the norm. And while it has some brilliant parts, the second and third books can be tedious and boring at times, as the book isn't structured like a standard novel modern readers would be used to. It is almost impossible to read this story in a long stretch, but it is rather enjoyable when read a few pages a day. I'm going to miss the time I've spent with these characters. <br /><br />Goodbye Aksinya. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9856108981114160112" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


